# Visualize empty droplets from CellBender
cbwhite_00= unlist(read.csv("/home/rstudio/time-series/cellbender/white_00.csv", header = FALSE))
UMAPPlot(swhite_00,cells.highlight=cbwhite_00)+theme_classic(base_size = 20)+theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),axis.title.y = element_blank(),legend.position = "none")
ggsave(filename = "empty_drop.eps",device = "eps",path = "/home/rstudio/time-series/figures/white_00/",width = 6,height = 4)


# Visualize percent mt content
swhite_00[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(swhite_00, pattern = "^MT-")
FeaturePlot(swhite_00,"percent.mt")


# No real cluster of empty droplets and high mitochondrial content cells
# Therefore, remove cells not detected in cellbender and remove cells with mt content > 10%
# Assuming that the cell cluster is pretty homogeneous, doublet removal is performed based on UMI count
doublets=rownames(swhite_00@meta.data)[swhite_00@meta.data$nCount_RNA>=49000]
# Cluster cells at different resolutions
swhite_00=FindNeighbors(swhite_00,reduction="scVI",graph.name="RNA_snn_scVI",dims=1:20)
Computing nearest neighbor graph
Computing SNN
swhite_00=FindClusters(swhite_00,resolution = .6,graph.name = "RNA_snn_scVI", verbose = FALSE)
UMAPPlot(swhite_00,label=TRUE,label.size=6)+theme_classic(base_size = 20)+theme(legend.position = "none",axis.title.x=element_blank(),axis.title.y=element_blank())
ggsave(filename = "cluster.eps",device = "eps",path = "/home/rstudio/time-series/figures/white_00/",width = 6,height = 4)

# Cluster 2 is enriched for mitotic terms. That makes me thing if the clustering is because of cell cycle effects
# Ans: Yes, it is. We could either regress for cell cycle effects, or it is a same cluster, so cell cycle effects should be averaged out anyway
i_1=FindMarkers(object = swhite_00,ident.1 = 2,ident.2=c(0,1,3),assay = "RNA",slot = "data",logfc.threshold = .5,verbose = FALSE,only.pos = TRUE)
i_1=subset.data.frame(i_1,subset = p_val_adj<.05)
